{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c00c57da-2a82-4710-b00b-ffa31c680f77","content":"","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_01QfUpCxc2vpMPxNyV3nVHiD","name":"report_intent","arguments":{"intent":"Running tests with crash dumps"},"type":"function"},{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_01C2cKfSFbTQS62Q96kLGDCQ","name":"bash","arguments":{"command":"cd /tmp/sv-eaf01678fca945cc866d30a874dbf04e && dotnet test --blame-crash 2>&1","description":"Run dotnet test with blame-crash for crash dump collection","initial_wait":60},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"Run dotnet test with blame-crash for crash dump collection"}],"interactionId":"20599f2f-f054-4c07-9aa1-14357026b604","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to run `dotnet test` and collect crash dumps if the test host crashes. To do this, I need to configure crash dump collection. There are a few ways to do this:\n\n1. Use the `DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump` environment variable to collect crash dumps from the .NET runtime itself.\n2. Use the `--collect` option with `dotnet test` to use a data collector.\n\nFor crash dump collection specifically when the test host crashes, the best approach is to use the environment variables:\n- `DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump=1` - enables mini dump collection\n\n\n- `DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType=4` - full dump (MiniDumpWithFullMemory)\n- `DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName` - path for the dump file\n\nHowever, the most straightforward approach is using the `--blame-crash` option, which is part of the blame data collector in `dotnet test` and is specifically designed for capturing crash dumps when the test host unexpectedly exits. I'll run the command with this flag.","outputTokens":514,"requestId":"340C:3793E1:CF6599:F109F6:69F402D6"},"id":"b6b3d65f-4544-4659-b148-84382df783f5","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:33:20.113Z","parentId":"e9b39439-3938-4582-9c67-49f72ce21c78"}
